<h1>Problem Set 1.1 ‚ÄĒ Solutions</h1>
<p class="book-ref">Strang, <em>Introduction to Linear Algebra</em> ‚ÄĒ Chapter 1.1</p>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P1 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q1</span><span class="prob-title">Describe geometrically all linear combinations</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="tabs">
      <button class="tab active" data-t="1a">Part (a)</button>
      <button class="tab" data-t="1b">Part (b)</button>
      <button class="tab" data-t="1c">Part (c)</button>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content active" id="t-1a">
      <div class="statement">Describe geometrically all linear combinations of <em class="vec col-r">[2,2]</em> and <em class="vec col-b">[6,9]</em>.</div>
      <p>A linear combination is c[2,2] + d[6,9]. Do these two vectors point in <em>different</em> directions?</p>
      <div class="math-block">[2,2] direction: slope = 2/2 = 1 (45¬į)<br>[6,9] direction: slope = 9/6 = 1.5 (different!)</div>
      <p>Since the two vectors are <strong>not parallel</strong> (one can't be written as a multiple of the other), their combinations sweep out the <strong>entire 2D plane ‚ĄĚ¬≤</strong>.</p>
      <div class="answer"><strong>Answer:</strong> All of ‚ĄĚ¬≤ ‚ÄĒ every point in the plane is reachable.</div>
      <div class="canvas-wrap"><canvas id="c1a" width="440" height="320"></canvas><p class="canvas-cap">Red and blue vectors span the whole plane ‚ÄĒ the green dots show a sample of combinations.</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content" id="t-1b">
      <div class="statement">Describe geometrically all linear combinations of <em class="vec col-r">[0,0,2]</em> and <em class="vec col-b">[0,2,0]</em> and <em class="vec col-g">[0,2,3]</em>.</div>
      <p>All three vectors have a <strong>0 in the first component</strong>. So any combination c¬∑[0,0,2] + d¬∑[0,2,0] + e¬∑[0,2,3] also has 0 in the first component:</p>
      <div class="math-block">combination = [0, 2d+2e, 2c+3e]</div>
      <p>No matter what c, d, e are, the x-component is always 0. So we can never leave the yz-plane (x=0).</p>
      <p>But within that plane, can we reach everything? The yz-parts are [2d+2e, 2c+3e]. With enough freedom in c,d,e we can reach any (y,z) with x=0 ‚ÄĒ so yes, <strong>the entire yz-plane</strong>.</p>
      <div class="answer"><strong>Answer:</strong> The yz-plane (all points with x = 0) ‚ÄĒ a flat plane through the origin in 3D space.</div>
      <div class="insight">Key idea: if every vector in your set has 0 in some component, combinations can never move in that direction. You're stuck in a lower-dimensional subspace.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content" id="t-1c">
      <div class="statement">Describe geometrically all linear combinations of <em class="vec col-r">[0,0,2]</em>, <em class="vec col-b">[0,2,0]</em>, <em class="vec col-g">[2,2,3]</em>.</div>
      <p>Now the third vector <strong>[2,2,3] has a non-zero first component</strong>. So we can reach any x-value by scaling it. Combined with the first two vectors covering all yz-directions, we can reach any (x,y,z).</p>
      <div class="math-block">c[0,0,2] + d[0,2,0] + e[2,2,3] = [2e, 2d+2e, 2c+3e]<br>Set x=any: e = x/2. Then adjust d,c freely for y,z.</div>
      <div class="answer"><strong>Answer:</strong> All of ‚ĄĚ¬≥ ‚ÄĒ the entire three-dimensional space.</div>
      <div class="insight">Adding [2,2,3] broke out of the yz-plane by contributing a non-zero x-component. This is exactly the idea of <em>linear independence</em> ‚ÄĒ each new independent vector adds a full new dimension.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P2 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q2</span><span class="prob-title">Draw v+w and v‚ąíw in a single xy plane</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">v = [4,1], w = [‚ąí2,2]. Draw v+w and v‚ąíw in a single xy plane.</div>
    <div class="math-block">v + w = [4+(‚ąí2), 1+2] = [2, 3]<br>v ‚ąí w = [4‚ąí(‚ąí2), 1‚ąí2] = [6, ‚ąí1]</div>
    <p><strong>Geometric meaning:</strong> v+w is the diagonal of the parallelogram formed by v and w. v‚ąíw is the <em>other</em> diagonal ‚ÄĒ equivalently, it's the arrow from the tip of w to the tip of v.</p>
    <div class="canvas-wrap"><canvas id="c2" width="440" height="360"></canvas><p class="canvas-cap">The parallelogram rule: v+w and v‚ąíw are the two diagonals.</p></div>
    <div class="answer"><strong>v + w = [2, 3] &nbsp;¬∑&nbsp; v ‚ąí w = [6, ‚ąí1]</strong></div>
    <div class="insight">Notice v+w and v‚ąíw are perpendicular when v and w have the same length (they form a rhombus). Here they're not equal length so the diagonals aren't perpendicular.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P3 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q3</span><span class="prob-title">Compute and draw v and w from v+w and v‚ąíw</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">If v+w = [5,1] and v‚ąíw = [1,5], compute and draw v and w.</div>
    <p>We have two equations. <strong>Add them:</strong></p>
    <div class="math-block">(v+w) + (v‚ąíw) = 2v ‚Üí [5,1]+[1,5] = [6,6] ‚Üí v = [3,3]</div>
    <p><strong>Subtract them:</strong></p>
    <div class="math-block">(v+w) ‚ąí (v‚ąíw) = 2w ‚Üí [5,1]‚ąí[1,5] = [4,‚ąí4] ‚Üí w = [2,‚ąí2]</div>
    <div class="answer"><strong>v = [3, 3] &nbsp;¬∑&nbsp; w = [2, ‚ąí2]</strong></div>
    <div class="canvas-wrap"><canvas id="c3" width="440" height="320"></canvas><p class="canvas-cap">v and w recovered; check: v+w=[5,1] ‚úď and v‚ąíw=[1,5] ‚úď</p></div>
    <div class="insight">This is a preview of solving linear equations ‚ÄĒ given the sums and differences, work backward to find the originals.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P4 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q4</span><span class="prob-title">Find components of 3v+w and cv+dw</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">v = [2,1], w = [‚ąí1,2]. Find components of 3v+w and cv+dw.</div>
    <div class="math-block">3v + w = 3[2,1] + [‚ąí1,2] = [6,3] + [‚ąí1,2] = [5, 5]<br><br>cv + dw = c[2,1] + d[‚ąí1,2] = [2c‚ąíd,  c+2d]</div>
    <div class="answer"><strong>3v + w = [5, 5] &nbsp;¬∑&nbsp; cv + dw = [2c‚ąíd, c+2d]</strong></div>
    <div class="insight">The general form [2c‚ąíd, c+2d] is important: for <em>any</em> target vector b = [b‚āĀ, b‚āā] we can ask "does there exist c,d such that 2c‚ąíd=b‚āĀ and c+2d=b‚āā?" Because v and w are independent, the answer is always yes ‚ÄĒ they span all of ‚ĄĚ¬≤.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P5 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q5</span><span class="prob-title">How do you know u, v, w lie in a plane?</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">u=[2,1,3], v=[1,‚ąí1,2], w=[‚ąí3,2]. Compute u+v+w and 2u+2v+2w. How do you know u, v, w lie in a plane? Also compute cv+dw.</div>
    <p>Wait ‚ÄĒ we need to check: w = [‚ąí3, 2] has only 2 components, but u and v have 3. Interpreting this as the problem written in a plane context, with:</p>
    <div class="math-block">u = [2, 1, 3],  v = [1, ‚ąí1, 2],  w = [‚ąí3, 2, ‚ąí5] (likely intended)</div>
    <p><strong>How to tell they lie in a plane:</strong> check if w = au + bv for some scalars. In many textbook problems w is constructed as a combination of u and v ‚ÄĒ if so, the three vectors are <em>linearly dependent</em> and span only a plane, not all of ‚ĄĚ¬≥.</p>
    <div class="math-block">u + v + w = [2+1‚ąí3, 1‚ąí1+2, 3+2‚ąí5] = [0, 2, 0]<br>2u + 2v + 2w = 2[0,2,0]  = [0, 4, 0]</div>
    <div class="answer"><strong>Key test:</strong> if w = c¬∑u + d¬∑v (i.e. w is a linear combination of u and v), then u, v, w all lie in the same plane through the origin. Three vectors in 3D lie in a plane exactly when one is a combination of the other two.</div>
    <div class="insight">The zero vector u+v+w=[0,2,0] hints at a relationship. If u+v+w were exactly 0 that would mean w=‚ąíu‚ąív ‚ÄĒ a clear dependency.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P6 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q6</span><span class="prob-title">Find c and d so cv+dw = (3,3,‚ąí6)</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">v = (1,‚ąí2,1), w = (0,1,‚ąí1). Find c,d so that cv+dw has components (3,3,‚ąí6).</div>
    <div class="math-block">c[1,‚ąí2,1] + d[0,1,‚ąí1] = [3, 3, ‚ąí6]</div>
    <p>Component equations:</p>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li><strong>x:</strong> c = 3</li>
      <li><strong>y:</strong> ‚ąí2c + d = 3 ‚Üí ‚ąí6 + d = 3 ‚Üí d = 9</li>
      <li><strong>z:</strong> c ‚ąí d = ‚ąí6 ‚Üí 3 ‚ąí 9 = ‚ąí6 ‚úď</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="answer"><strong>c = 3, d = 9</strong></div>
    <div class="math-block">Check: 3[1,‚ąí2,1] + 9[0,1,‚ąí1] = [3,‚ąí6,3]+[0,9,‚ąí9] = [3, 3, ‚ąí6] ‚úď</div>
    <div class="insight">Notice the z-equation gave us a consistency check for free (it was automatically satisfied). This happens because we only have 2 unknowns (c, d) but 3 equations ‚ÄĒ it only works if the target vector [3,3,‚ąí6] lies in the plane spanned by v and w.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P7 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q7</span><span class="prob-title">Mark all nine combinations in the xy plane</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">Mark all nine combinations c[2,0] + d[0,1] with c,d ‚ąą {0,1,2}.</div>
    <div class="math-block">Combinations: (2c, d) for c‚ąą{0,1,2}, d‚ąą{0,1,2}<br><br>= (0,0), (0,1), (0,2),<br>  (2,0), (2,1), (2,2),<br>  (4,0), (4,1), (4,2)</div>
    <p>These form a <strong>3√ó3 grid of points</strong> ‚ÄĒ the corners and interior of a rectangle.</p>
    <div class="canvas-wrap"><canvas id="c7" width="440" height="300"></canvas><p class="canvas-cap">Nine points: c‚ąą{0,1,2}, d‚ąą{0,1,2}</p></div>
    <div class="answer"><strong>9 points forming a rectangular grid</strong> at x‚ąą{0,2,4}, y‚ąą{0,1,2}.</div>
    <div class="insight">If c and d were allowed to be <em>any</em> real numbers, the points would fill the entire first quadrant (and beyond). Restricting c,d to {0,1,2} gives discrete grid points instead of a continuous region.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P8 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q8</span><span class="prob-title">Parallelogram diagonals</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">The parallelogram in Figure 1.1 has diagonal v+w. What is its other diagonal? If three corners are (1,1), (4,2), (1,3), what are all three possible fourth corners?</div>
    <hr class="light">
    <p><strong>Part 1 ‚ÄĒ Other diagonal:</strong> In a parallelogram with sides v and w from the origin, the two diagonals are v+w and v‚ąíw (one goes from tip of v to tip of w, the other is the main diagonal). So <strong>the other diagonal is v‚ąíw</strong>.</p>
    <hr class="light">
    <p><strong>Part 2 ‚ÄĒ Three corners: (1,1), (4,2), (1,3).</strong> A parallelogram has 4 corners; each pair of opposite corners shares a midpoint (the centre). Label our three known corners A=(1,1), B=(4,2), C=(1,3). The fourth corner D depends on <em>which</em> two are opposite:</p>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li><strong>A and B opposite:</strong> midpoint = (2.5, 1.5) = midpoint of C and D ‚Üí D = (5‚ąí1, 3‚ąí3) = <strong>(4, 0)</strong></li>
      <li><strong>A and C opposite:</strong> midpoint = (1, 2) = midpoint of B and D ‚Üí D = (2‚ąí4, 4‚ąí2) = <strong>(‚ąí2, 2)</strong></li>
      <li><strong>B and C opposite:</strong> midpoint = (2.5, 2.5) = midpoint of A and D ‚Üí D = (5‚ąí1, 5‚ąí1) = <strong>(4, 4)</strong></li>
    </ol>
    <div class="answer"><strong>Three possible 4th corners: (4,0), (‚ąí2,2), (4,4)</strong></div>
    <div class="canvas-wrap"><canvas id="c8" width="440" height="360"></canvas><p class="canvas-cap">Three parallelograms ‚ÄĒ each uses the same three points with a different fourth corner.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź P9 ‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź‚ēź -->
<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q9</span><span class="prob-title">Three corners ‚Üí vector sum</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">If three corners of a parallelogram are (2,0), (0,3), and (4,3), find all possible fourth corners and the vector sum.</div>
    <p>Same midpoint method. Let A=(2,0), B=(0,3), C=(4,3).</p>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li>A,B opposite: midpoint=(1,1.5), D = (2‚ąí0, 3‚ąí3) = <strong>(2,3) ‚ÄĒ wait</strong>: D=(2¬∑1‚ąí4, 2¬∑1.5‚ąí3) = (‚ąí2, 0)</li>
      <li>A,C opposite: midpoint=(3,1.5), D=(6‚ąí0, 3‚ąí3)=<strong>(6,0)</strong></li>
      <li>B,C opposite: midpoint=(2,3), D=(4‚ąí2,6‚ąí0)=<strong>(2,6)</strong></li>
    </ol>
    <div class="answer"><strong>Three possible 4th corners: (‚ąí2,0), (6,0), (2,6)</strong></div>
    <p><strong>Vector sum</strong> in each parallelogram = the diagonal from origin (if one corner is origin) = the sum of the two side vectors.</p>
  </div>
</div>

