<div class="prob">
  <div class="prob-header"><span class="prob-num">Q13</span><span class="prob-title">Clock vectors</span></div>
  <div class="prob-body">
    <div class="statement">(a) Sum of 12 clock vectors. (b) Remove 2:00 ‚ÄĒ why do 11 add to 8:00? (c) Components of 2:00 vector v = (cos őł, sin őł).</div>
    <hr class="light">
    <p><strong>(a)</strong> The 12 unit vectors point at 1:00, 2:00, ‚Ä¶, 12:00 ‚ÄĒ equally spaced by 30¬į around the circle. By symmetry, each vector at angle őł is exactly cancelled by the one at őł+180¬į. All 12 cancel perfectly:</p>
    <div class="answer"><strong>Sum of all 12 = (0, 0)</strong> ‚ÄĒ the zero vector.</div>
    <hr class="light">
    <p><strong>(b)</strong> If total = 0 and we remove the 2:00 vector v, the remaining 11 vectors sum to <strong>‚ąív</strong>, which points in the opposite direction: toward 8:00.</p>
    <div class="answer"><strong>11 vectors sum to ‚ąív‚āā:‚āÄ‚āÄ</strong>, which points toward 8:00 (directly opposite 2:00).</div>
    <hr class="light">
    <p><strong>(c)</strong> 2:00 is at angle őł = 60¬į from the positive x-axis (measuring counterclockwise from 3:00 position, 2:00 is 30¬į above horizontal = 60¬į from east).</p>
    <div class="math-block">v‚āā:‚āÄ‚āÄ = (cos 60¬į, sin 60¬į) = (1/2, ‚ąö3/2) ‚Čą (0.5, 0.866)</div>
    <div class="canvas-wrap"><canvas id="c13" width="380" height="380"></canvas><p class="canvas-cap">12 clock unit vectors ‚ÄĒ they sum to zero by symmetry.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

